<<nobr>><h2>Final Self Reflection</h2>
<small>Jester is overall satisfied with their speech performances during this course, and has synthesized a final self reflection (in contrast to the inventory-style reflections).</small><</nobr>>

<strong>Consider the following reflection questions and choose a few that are most relevant or significant for YOU to answer. Include specific examples in your answers.</strong>
# <strong>What were your biggest perceived challenges as a speaker when you started the course and how did you overcome those challenges?</strong> "Historically, my biggest public speaking challenge has been attempting to mangle my ideas to fit into the neat boxes of prescribed formal structure in an academic setting. I definitely made significant strides in this area, especially with '[[Poe endures]].'  My instructor and I concur that I fit my entire poem perfectly into the requirements of our 6-step outline process."
# <strong>What changes occurred in your perception of public speaking? Why do you think this change occurred?</strong> "None of my sentiment around the discipline changed at all over this course, however my aversion to formality and rigidity in public speaking settings due to the inauthentic sheen that often accompanies it has intensified significantly. Even at times during my instructor's examples, I found parts forced, and I believe a more casual relationship to the structure could have nullified this perception."
# <strong>What were your biggest accomplishments in class? What are you most proud of?</strong> "With our final speech assignment in this course, I managed to encourage a group of my peers to enthusiastically recite a line of poetry in public. Even professional poetry instructors often struggle to get students interested, and I am quite proud of my success in this area."
# <strong>What speaking skills will you continue to develop beyond class?</strong> "Ever since the 2019 coronavirus pandemic, I have worn some form of facial PPE in public, and this class helped me to notice that this change has lead me to regress into many of my former poor habbits with breath control. I did not have much opportunity to work on this deficiency in class, but I will certainly be focusing on it moving forward.
# <strong>What kind of speaker are you as a result of your experiences in this class?</strong> "I remain largely the type of speaker to spit in the face of convention, take up space, and push boundaries with unconvential ideas and experimental form, but this course has strengthened my ability to play by the books when required. I am much more capable of adhering to traditional wisdom and playing things safer than I was before this course."
# <strong>In what ways has collaboration with your instructor/speech coach or peers impacted your learning and or speaking abilities?</strong> "The greatest benefit of my collaboration in this course was the dialogue I opened with my instructor over pushing the form of our final tribute speech (seeing as it was permitted to be read from a manuscript). This eventually resulted in the formation of a much more impactful tribute to my subject (Edgar Allan Poe) than I could have accomplished with mere prose."
